	<ul class="children">
	<li class="comment even depth-3" id="li-comment-423211">
		<article id="comment-423211" class="comment">
			<footer class="comment-meta">
				<div class="comment-author vcard">
					<span class="fn">morganovich</span> <span class="sep">|</span> <a href="http://www.aei-ideas.org/2014/04/creative-destruction-2013-newspaper-ad-revenue-continued-its-precipitous-free-fall-and-its-probably-not-over-yet/comment-page-1/#comment-423211"><time pubdate datetime="2014-04-26T13:34:40-04:00">April 26, 2014 at 1:34 pm</time></a>
									</div><!-- .comment-author .vcard -->

				
			</footer>

			<div class="comment-content"><p>well, sort of.</p>
<p>1. that sort of local &#8220;indie&#8221; advertising is incredibly cheap.  it&#8217;s not that big a piece of revenues.</p>
<p>2. that is precisely the space at which the new mobile advertising platforms, exchanges, and engines are aimed.  rather than scattergunning a whole zipcode, they will push you ads based on what you are near and known individual preferences.  that ad space is now directly in the cross-hairs of the next Schumptarian salvo.</p>
<p>3. the place the local papers and the little indie papers really got hurt were classifieds.  job listings, real estate, stuff for sale, apartments for rent etc used to be the real bread and butter.  those were the ads that really paid and they are never going back to print.</p>
</div>

			<div class="reply">
				<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2014/04/creative-destruction-2013-newspaper-ad-revenue-continued-its-precipitous-free-fall-and-its-probably-not-over-yet/?replytocom=423211#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-423211", "423211", "respond", "128638")'>Reply <span>&darr;</span></a>			</div><!-- .reply -->
